The '''Mormon History Association''' ('''MHA''') is an independent, [[non-profit organization]] dedicated to the study and understanding of all aspects of [[Mormon]] history to promote understanding, scholarly research, and publication in the field. MHA was founded in December 1965 at the [[American Historical Association]] (AHA) meeting in [[San Francisco, California|San Francisco]] under the leadership of [[Latter-day Saint]] and [[list of historians|historian]], [[Leonard J. Arrington]]. In 1972, MHA became an independent organization with its own annual conferences and publications. ''The Journal of Mormon History'', the official biennial publication of the association, began publication in 1974. MHA also publishes the quarterly ''Mormon History Newsletter'' and is an affiliate of both AHA and the [[Western History Association]].
MHA "welcome[s] all who are interested in the Mormon past, irrespective of religious affiliation, academic training, or world location." Its members are composed of people both within and without [[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]] (LDS Church) and the [[Community of Christ]], including those who reject [[Mormonism]]. {{Citation needed|date=April 2010}}
